\begin{abstract}
\noindent
Louis Bachelier's 1900 doctoral thesis, \emph{Th\'eorie de la Sp\'eculation}, is one of the earliest mathematical foundations of modern quantitative finance. Long before the standardization of stochastic calculus in financial economics, Bachelier introduced a probabilistic framework for market price fluctuations and derived option-pricing relations based on what is now recognized as arithmetic Brownian motion. This paper provides a modern, reproducible reconstruction of Bachelier's theory. We reformulate the core model in contemporary notation, derive its martingale and variance-scaling properties, recover the Bachelier European call pricing formula, and validate the formula numerically through Monte Carlo simulation. We further compare the Bachelier model with Black--Scholes in a low-relative-volatility regime, emphasizing both the historical continuity and the structural differences between arithmetic and geometric price dynamics. The contribution of this paper is not to introduce a new option-pricing theory, but to provide an open, transparent, and computationally reproducible bridge between Bachelier's original work and modern quantitative finance. The paper concludes by discussing the limitations of the arithmetic model, especially the possibility of negative prices, and by proposing a reproducibility framework for historical financial mathematics.

\vspace{6pt}
\noindent\textbf{Keywords:} Bachelier; Theory of Speculation; Arithmetic Brownian Motion; Option Pricing; Quantitative Finance; Monte Carlo Simulation; Reproducible Research; Open Science

\vspace{4pt}
\noindent\textbf{JEL Classification:} C15, C63, G12, G13, B26
\end{abstract}

\newpage
\setcounter{page}{1}

% ==================================================================
\section{Introduction}
% ==================================================================

The history of quantitative finance is often narrated through the development of modern portfolio theory, the Black--Scholes--Merton option-pricing framework, and the rise of computational methods in financial markets. Yet one of the earliest mathematical treatments of speculation predates these developments by several decades. In 1900, Louis Bachelier submitted his doctoral thesis, \emph{Th\'eorie de la Sp\'eculation}, in which he proposed a probabilistic approach to price fluctuations and derived option-pricing relations using a model that can be interpreted today as arithmetic Brownian motion \citep{bachelier1900}.

Bachelier's work is remarkable for at least three reasons. First, it introduced probabilistic reasoning into the study of market prices before financial economics had acquired its modern mathematical vocabulary. Second, it anticipated ideas that later became central to stochastic processes, derivative pricing, and risk modelling. Third, it treated contingent financial contracts as payoff functions whose values could be studied through probability laws.

This paper revisits Bachelier's theory from a modern reproducibility perspective. Rather than treating the 1900 thesis only as a historical document, we reconstruct its mathematical core and implement it as an open-source computational project. The objective is to make Bachelier's model transparent, testable, and educational for students, researchers, and practitioners in quantitative finance.

This paper makes four contributions. First, it reformulates Bachelier's price process in contemporary notation and derives its basic martingale and variance properties. Second, it presents the Bachelier European call pricing formula and explains its connection to the normal distribution. Third, it validates the formula numerically through Monte Carlo simulation and visualizes the square-root-of-time scaling of at-the-money option prices. Fourth, it situates the model relative to Black--Scholes, emphasizing both the continuity between the two frameworks and the limitations of Bachelier's arithmetic specification.

The remainder of the paper is organized as follows. Section~2 reviews the relevant literature. Section~3 defines the historical source and scope of the reproduction. Section~4 presents the arithmetic Brownian motion model. Section~5 derives the Bachelier option-pricing formula. Section~6 describes the computational methodology. Section~7 reports numerical results. Section~8 compares Bachelier with Black--Scholes. Section~9 discusses interpretation. Section~10 examines limitations. Section~11 presents the open-science reproducibility framework. Section~12 concludes.

% ==================================================================
\section{Literature Review}
% ==================================================================

Bachelier's \emph{Th\'eorie de la Sp\'eculation} is now widely recognized as one of the earliest mathematical treatments of financial markets \citep{bachelier1900}. Its later dissemination in English was helped by its inclusion in \citet{cootner1964}, which placed Bachelier's work within the emerging literature on random stock prices and speculative markets \citep{bachelier1964}.

The probabilistic view of price fluctuations developed further in the mid-twentieth century. \citet{osborne1959} examined Brownian motion in the stock market and contributed to the empirical and theoretical interpretation of price changes as stochastic processes. At the same time, \citet{mandelbrot1963} challenged Gaussian assumptions by documenting large variations and heavy-tailed behaviour in speculative prices. These developments show both the historical importance of Bachelier's model and the need to understand its limitations.

The modern option-pricing literature is usually associated with \citet{blackscholes1973} and \citet{merton1973}, who introduced a no-arbitrage framework based on geometric Brownian motion and dynamic replication. Earlier, \citet{samuelson1965} developed a rational theory of warrant pricing, helping to connect stochastic modelling with derivative valuation. The Black--Scholes--Merton model differs from Bachelier's model in several fundamental respects: prices are lognormally distributed, remain positive, and are priced under a risk-neutral measure using a self-financing hedging argument. Nonetheless, both frameworks share a common mathematical foundation in continuous-time stochastic modelling.

From a stochastic-process perspective, the Bachelier model is one of the simplest continuous-time Gaussian models. Standard references such as \citet{feller1968}, \citet{karatzas1998}, and \citet{shreve2004} provide the mathematical background for Brownian motion, martingales, and stochastic calculus. From a financial-engineering perspective, \citet{hull2018} presents modern derivative pricing theory, while \citet{bjork2009} provides a rigorous treatment of arbitrage pricing in continuous time.

Bachelier-style normal models remain relevant in certain areas of modern finance. In particular, normal-volatility models appear in interest-rate markets and in settings where absolute changes may be more natural than proportional returns. The SABR literature, for example, includes the normal model as a limiting or special case in volatility-smile modelling \citep{hagan2002}.

The contribution of this paper is not to introduce a new pricing model. Rather, it provides a self-contained and reproducible reconstruction of Bachelier's original mathematical insight using modern notation, Python implementation, numerical validation, and open-science infrastructure.

% ==================================================================
\section{Historical Source and Scope of Reproduction}
% ==================================================================

The primary historical source is Bachelier's 1900 thesis, \emph{Th\'eorie de la Sp\'eculation}, published in the \emph{Annales Scientifiques de l'\'Ecole Normale Sup\'erieure} \citep{bachelier1900}. The original work combines institutional descriptions of the Paris market with mathematical analysis of speculation, forward transactions, premiums, and probability laws.

This paper does not attempt to reproduce every institutional detail of the original thesis. Many market conventions discussed by Bachelier were specific to the Paris financial market of the late nineteenth century. Instead, we focus on the mathematical core that remains central to quantitative finance:

\begin{enumerate}[label=(\roman*), leftmargin=2.2em]
\item the representation of price changes through a probability law;
\item the arithmetic Brownian motion interpretation of price dynamics;
\item the martingale intuition underlying the absence of directional bias;
\item the variance-scaling structure of Brownian fluctuations;
\item the valuation of option-like payoffs through the normal distribution.
\end{enumerate}

The reproduction is therefore mathematical and computational rather than archival. The goal is to translate Bachelier's core ideas into a modern framework that can be inspected, executed, tested, and extended.

\begin{remark}
The paper uses modern notation and terminology. Terms such as Brownian motion, martingale, Monte Carlo simulation, and risk-neutral valuation are not presented as Bachelier's original vocabulary. They are used to express his ideas in contemporary mathematical finance language.
\end{remark}

% ==================================================================
\section{The Bachelier Model}
% ==================================================================

\subsection{Model Specification}

Let \(P_t\) denote the price of an asset at time \(t\). The Bachelier model assumes that price changes follow an arithmetic Brownian motion:

\begin{equation}
P_t = P_0 + \sigma W_t,
\label{eq:bachelier-process}
\end{equation}

where \(P_0\) is the initial price, \(\sigma > 0\) is the arithmetic volatility parameter, and \(W_t\) is a standard Brownian motion.

Equivalently, in differential notation,

\begin{equation}
dP_t = \sigma\,dW_t.
\label{eq:bachelier-sde}
\end{equation}

Unlike geometric Brownian motion, this specification describes absolute price changes rather than proportional returns. The random variable \(P_t\) is normally distributed:

\begin{equation}
P_t \sim \mathcal{N}(P_0,\sigma^2 t).
\label{eq:normal-price-distribution}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Martingale Property}

\begin{proposition}[Martingale Property]
Under the Bachelier model,
\[
\mathbb{E}[P_t]=P_0.
\]
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
Using equation~\eqref{eq:bachelier-process},
\[
\mathbb{E}[P_t]
=
\mathbb{E}[P_0+\sigma W_t]
=
P_0+\sigma\mathbb{E}[W_t].
\]
Since \(\mathbb{E}[W_t]=0\), it follows that
\[
\mathbb{E}[P_t]=P_0.
\]
\end{proof}

The martingale property expresses the idea that, absent a drift term, the expected future price equals the current price. This does not imply that realized prices are constant. It means that the model contains no directional bias.

\subsection{Variance Scaling}

\begin{proposition}[Linear Variance Growth]
Under the Bachelier model,
\[
\Var(P_t)=\sigma^2 t.
\]
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
Since \(P_t=P_0+\sigma W_t\) and \(P_0\) is deterministic,
\[
\Var(P_t)=\Var(\sigma W_t)=\sigma^2\Var(W_t).
\]
For standard Brownian motion, \(\Var(W_t)=t\). Therefore,
\[
\Var(P_t)=\sigma^2 t.
\]
\end{proof}

The standard deviation is therefore

\begin{equation}
\sqrt{\Var(P_t)} = \sigma\sqrt{t}.
\label{eq:sqrt-time-volatility}
\end{equation}

This square-root-of-time scaling remains a central principle in finance, although its practical use depends on the validity of the underlying assumptions.

% ==================================================================
\section{Bachelier Option Pricing Formula}
% ==================================================================

\subsection{European Call Payoff}

Consider a European call option with strike \(K\) and maturity \(T\). Its payoff is

\begin{equation}
(P_T-K)^+ = \max(P_T-K,0).
\end{equation}

Under the Bachelier model,

\begin{equation}
P_T=P_0+\sigma\sqrt{T}Z,
\end{equation}

where \(Z\sim\mathcal{N}(0,1)\). Define

\begin{equation}
d=\frac{P_0-K}{\sigma\sqrt{T}}.
\label{eq:bachelier-d}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Closed-Form Formula}

The Bachelier call price is

\begin{equation}
C=(P_0-K)\Phi(d)+\sigma\sqrt{T}\phi(d),
\label{eq:bachelier-call}
\end{equation}

where \(\Phi\) is the standard normal cumulative distribution function and \(\phi\) is the standard normal density.

\begin{proposition}[Bachelier Call Formula]
If \(P_T=P_0+\sigma\sqrt{T}Z\), with \(Z\sim\mathcal{N}(0,1)\), then
\[
\mathbb{E}[(P_T-K)^+]
=
(P_0-K)\Phi(d)+\sigma\sqrt{T}\phi(d),
\]
with \(d\) defined by equation~\eqref{eq:bachelier-d}.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
The call value is
\[
C=\mathbb{E}[(P_0-K+\sigma\sqrt{T}Z)^+].
\]
The payoff is positive when
\[
Z>-d.
\]
Therefore,
\[
C=\int_{-d}^{\infty}(P_0-K+\sigma\sqrt{T}z)\phi(z)\,dz.
\]
Separating the integral gives
\[
C=(P_0-K)\int_{-d}^{\infty}\phi(z)\,dz
+
\sigma\sqrt{T}\int_{-d}^{\infty}z\phi(z)\,dz.
\]
Using
\[
\int_{-d}^{\infty}\phi(z)\,dz=\Phi(d)
\]
and
\[
\int_{-d}^{\infty}z\phi(z)\,dz=\phi(d),
\]
we obtain
\[
C=(P_0-K)\Phi(d)+\sigma\sqrt{T}\phi(d).
\]
\end{proof}

\subsection{At-the-Money Scaling}

When \(K=P_0\), equation~\eqref{eq:bachelier-d} gives \(d=0\), so

\begin{equation}
C_{\mathrm{ATM}}=\sigma\sqrt{T}\phi(0).
\label{eq:atm-scaling}
\end{equation}

This expression makes the square-root-of-time structure explicit. The at-the-money option value grows proportionally to \(\sqrt{T}\), not linearly in \(T\).

% ==================================================================
\section{Computational Methodology}
% ==================================================================

\subsection{Implementation Design}

The computational reproduction is implemented in Python using NumPy, SciPy, Matplotlib, and Pytest. The repository is designed to remain readable and educational while supporting reproducible numerical validation.

The implementation contains two main scripts:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2.2em]
\item \texttt{src/brownian\_motion.py}: simulation of arithmetic Brownian motion and verification of martingale and variance properties;
\item \texttt{src/option\_pricing.py}: Bachelier option pricing, Monte Carlo validation, and comparison with Black--Scholes.
\end{itemize}

The numerical experiments use fixed random seeds. This makes the figures and reported outputs reproducible from a clean clone of the repository.

\subsection{Baseline Parameters}

The baseline parameters used in the computational reproduction are reported in Table~\ref{tab:parameters}.

\begin{table}[htbp]
\centering
\caption{Baseline numerical parameters used in the reproduction.}
\label{tab:parameters}
\begin{tabular}{lll}
\toprule
Parameter & Value & Interpretation \\
\midrule
\(P_0\) & 100 & Initial price \\
\(\sigma\) & 2 & Arithmetic volatility \\
\(T\) & 1 & Time horizon / maturity \\
\(N_{\mathrm{steps}}\) & 250 & Number of time steps in path simulation \\
\(N_{\mathrm{paths}}\) & 5,000 & Number of simulated Brownian paths \\
\(N_{\mathrm{MC}}\) & 500,000 & Number of Monte Carlo samples for option pricing \\
Random seeds & 42 and 7 & Reproducibility controls \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsection{Testing Protocol}

The repository includes automated tests in the \texttt{tests/} directory. The tests verify:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2.2em]
\item correct simulation shapes;
\item initialization of all paths at \(P_0\);
\item reproducibility under fixed seeds;
\item theoretical variance scaling;
\item numerical martingale behaviour;
\item Bachelier at-the-money option formula;
\item Monte Carlo consistency with the closed-form formula;
\item Black--Scholes benchmark behaviour;
\item error handling for invalid inputs.
\end{itemize}

Continuous integration is implemented through GitHub Actions. Each push or pull request can run the test suite, execute the scripts, and verify that the expected figures are generated.

% ==================================================================
\section{Numerical Results}
% ==================================================================

\subsection{Arithmetic Brownian Motion}

The first numerical experiment simulates sample paths of

\[
P_t=P_0+\sigma W_t.
\]

The code generates independent Gaussian increments

\[
\Delta P_t \sim \mathcal{N}(0,\sigma^2\Delta t)
\]

and constructs price paths by cumulative summation. The empirical mean and variance are then compared with their theoretical counterparts.

For the baseline configuration \(P_0=100\), \(\sigma=2\), \(T=1\), \(N_{\mathrm{steps}}=250\), and \(N_{\mathrm{paths}}=5{,}000\), the theoretical terminal variance is

\[
\sigma^2T=4.
\]

The reproducible simulation reports a terminal empirical mean of approximately \(100.0254\), a terminal empirical variance of approximately \(3.9376\), and a maximum deviation of the empirical mean from \(P_0\) of approximately \(0.0372\). These values are consistent with the martingale and variance-scaling properties of the model.

Figure~\ref{fig:brownian-motion} shows simulated price paths and verifies the linear variance growth.

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{figures/fig1_random_walk_martingale.png}
\caption{Simulated arithmetic Brownian motion under the Bachelier model. The left panel shows sample paths, the empirical mean, and the one-standard-deviation envelope. The right panel compares empirical variance with the theoretical variance \(\sigma^2 t\).}
\label{fig:brownian-motion}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Option-Pricing Validation}

The second experiment validates the Bachelier closed-form call formula by Monte Carlo simulation. Terminal prices are simulated as

\[
P_T=P_0+\sigma\sqrt{T}Z,
\]

and the Monte Carlo estimator is

\begin{equation}
\widehat{C}_{MC}
=
\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^{N}\max(P_T^{(i)}-K,0).
\end{equation}

For the at-the-money baseline case \(P_0=K=100\), \(\sigma=2\), and \(T=1\), the closed-form value is

\begin{equation}
C_{\mathrm{ATM}}
=
2\phi(0)
\approx 0.79788456.
\end{equation}

Using \(500{,}000\) Monte Carlo samples and the fixed seed specified in the implementation, the simulation produces a Monte Carlo estimate close to the analytical value. The numerical difference is small relative to the estimated Monte Carlo uncertainty.

\begin{table}[htbp]
\centering
\caption{Baseline numerical validation of the Bachelier ATM call price.}
\label{tab:option-validation}
\begin{tabular}{ll}
\toprule
Quantity & Baseline value \\
\midrule
Closed-form Bachelier ATM call price & \(0.79788456\) \\
Monte Carlo sample size & \(500{,}000\) \\
Monte Carlo estimate & \(0.79774645\) \\
Monte Carlo standard error & \(0.00165132\) \\
Absolute pricing difference & \(0.00013812\) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Figure~\ref{fig:option-pricing} presents the at-the-money square-root-of-time scaling and a comparison between Bachelier and Black--Scholes prices.

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{figures/fig2_option_pricing.png}
\caption{Bachelier option-pricing experiments. The left panel shows the square-root-of-time scaling of at-the-money call prices. The right panel compares Bachelier and Black--Scholes call prices under a low-relative-volatility calibration.}
\label{fig:option-pricing}
\end{figure}

% ==================================================================
\section{Comparison with Black--Scholes}
% ==================================================================

The Black--Scholes model assumes geometric Brownian motion:

\begin{equation}
dS_t=\mu S_t\,dt+\sigma_{BS}S_t\,dW_t.
\end{equation}

This specification implies lognormal prices and preserves positivity. By contrast, the Bachelier model assumes arithmetic price changes and therefore produces normally distributed prices. The two models are conceptually different, but they can be locally close when relative volatility is small.

To compare them, the arithmetic volatility in Bachelier is matched locally to Black--Scholes through

\begin{equation}
\sigma_{\mathrm{Bach}}\approx\sigma_{BS}S_0.
\end{equation}

This approximation follows from linearizing proportional price changes around the current level \(S_0\). In that regime, a small proportional shock \(\sigma_{BS}S_0dW_t\) behaves like an arithmetic shock with absolute volatility \(\sigma_{\mathrm{Bach}}\).

The comparison is historically meaningful. Bachelier introduced a normal price model and a corresponding option-pricing formula. Black--Scholes later introduced a geometric model that guarantees price positivity and supports no-arbitrage pricing under a risk-neutral measure. Bachelier is therefore not a failed version of Black--Scholes; it is a different modelling architecture, historically prior and mathematically simpler, that remains useful in certain modern settings, including normal-volatility markets and interest-rate modelling.

% ==================================================================
\section{Discussion}
% ==================================================================

The results show that Bachelier's model remains mathematically coherent within its own assumptions. The simulated price process behaves as predicted: its empirical mean remains close to the initial price, and its variance grows approximately linearly with time. The option-pricing experiment also confirms the closed-form formula through Monte Carlo validation.

The comparison with Black--Scholes clarifies the relationship between the two models. Bachelier models absolute price changes; Black--Scholes models proportional price changes. Bachelier prices are therefore normal-model prices, while Black--Scholes prices are lognormal-model prices. At low relative volatility and near the current price, the two frameworks can produce similar values. Away from that local regime, their structural differences become more important.

From a historical perspective, Bachelier's achievement is not diminished by the later dominance of geometric Brownian motion. His work introduced the key idea that financial contracts can be valued by integrating payoffs against probability distributions. This idea remains central to modern pricing theory, even though the probability measures, dynamics, and arbitrage arguments have evolved substantially.

From a reproducibility perspective, the reconstruction demonstrates that foundational mathematical-finance papers can be treated as executable research objects. A historical theory can be restated, coded, tested, visualized, and made available for inspection.

% ==================================================================
\section{Limitations}
% ==================================================================

The main limitation of the Bachelier model is that prices are normally distributed. Therefore,

\[
\Prob(P_t<0)>0
\]

whenever \(\sigma>0\) and \(t>0\). For equities or strictly positive assets, this is structurally unrealistic. In the baseline numerical setting used in this paper, the probability of negative terminal prices is essentially negligible because \(P_0/(\sigma\sqrt{T})\) is very large. However, the theoretical limitation remains important.

A second limitation is the absence of drift, interest rates, funding costs, dividends, transaction costs, liquidity effects, and risk premia in the simplest version of the model. These elements matter in modern financial markets and are central to arbitrage-pricing theory.

A third limitation concerns distributional symmetry. Arithmetic Brownian motion implies symmetric Gaussian price changes. Empirical financial returns often display skewness, heavy tails, volatility clustering, jumps, and regime dependence \citep{mandelbrot1963,merton1976}. The Bachelier model therefore cannot be treated as a complete empirical model of financial markets.

A fourth limitation concerns the reproduction itself. This paper reconstructs selected mathematical elements of Bachelier's theory, not every institutional component of the original thesis. The objective is therefore not archival completeness, but modern mathematical and computational reconstruction.

% ==================================================================
\section{Reproducibility and Open-Science Framework}
% ==================================================================

A central contribution of this paper is methodological: it treats a historical mathematical-finance result as a reproducible open-source research object.

The repository accompanying this paper includes:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2.2em]
\item source code for simulations and pricing experiments;
\item fixed random seeds for reproducibility;
\item generated figures;
\item automated tests;
\item continuous integration through GitHub Actions;
\item citation metadata through \texttt{CITATION.cff};
\item authorship information through \texttt{AUTHORS.md};
\item reproducibility documentation through \texttt{REPRODUCIBILITY.md};
\item an open-source MIT license.
\end{itemize}

This structure is designed to support transparent research. A reader should be able to clone the repository, install the dependencies, run the scripts, reproduce the figures, and verify the numerical tests.

The broader objective is to develop a reproducible research standard for historical quantitative finance. Foundational papers should not only be cited; they should be reconstructed, tested, visualized, and made accessible through open scientific infrastructure.

% ==================================================================
\section{Conclusion}
% ==================================================================

Bachelier's \emph{Th\'eorie de la Sp\'eculation} remains one of the foundational works in quantitative finance. Its significance lies not only in its historical priority, but also in its conceptual clarity: market fluctuations can be studied probabilistically, contingent claims can be represented by payoff functions, and option values can be derived from probability distributions.

This paper has provided a modern, reproducible reconstruction of Bachelier's theory. We reformulated the arithmetic Brownian motion model in contemporary notation, derived its martingale and variance properties, recovered the Bachelier call pricing formula, validated the formula numerically, and compared the model with Black--Scholes under low relative volatility.

The reconstruction also highlights the model's limitations. Arithmetic Brownian motion permits negative prices, assumes symmetric Gaussian fluctuations, and does not capture many empirical features of financial markets. Nevertheless, these limitations should be understood in context. Bachelier's work opened a mathematical path that later developments refined, extended, and transformed.

For Alpha Stochastic Research, this project represents the first step in an open-source research program dedicated to reproducing and modernizing foundational works in quantitative finance. The goal is to connect history, mathematics, computation, and open science in a transparent and reproducible framework.

